				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As we await an official presidential response to <a href="//douthat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/11/05/republicans-fought-the-future-and-the-future-lost/?module=BlogPost-Title&amp;version=Blog%20Main&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;action=Click&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Body">last night&#8217;s Democratic debacle</a>, here are two quotes that seem likely to frame the political class&#8217;s discussion ofÂ how the president might respond. First, <a href="//www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/11/obama-reboot-112432.html#.VFo4mPQfXlQ">from Politico</a>, days before the drubbing, when the White House could still hope for just a modest setback at the polls:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Administration officials tell us that Obamaâs political and policy teams are planning a big counterattack if the Republicans win the Senateâintroducing a slate of legislative proposals and executive actions on immigration, infrastructure and early childhood education that are popular with the Democratic base and that he will dare the GOP to oppose.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And second, from an anonymous Dem bigwig <a href="//www.businessinsider.com/elections-are-democratic-disaster-2014-11">talking to Business Insider</a> last night:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style="color: #000000;">The Democratic insider who described election night as a &#8220;bloodbath&#8221; also used the tidal wave metaphor â and that person laid blame for the wipeout squarely at Obama&#8217;s feet.</p>
<p style="color: #000000;">&#8220;This is a tsunami. Heads will roll at 1600. And if they don&#8217;t, shame,&#8221; the insider said, adding, &#8220;The president has 60 days to clean house, regrow his spine, and lay out an aggressive, centrist agenda. If he fails at any of those, he might as well just start writing his memoir.&#8221;</p>
</blockquote>
<p style="color: #000000;">I&#8217;m guessing that if you pressed the insider on what so-called aggressive centrism would look like, the words &#8220;Bowles-Simpson&#8221; and &#8220;grand bargain&#8221; would tumble quickly from his lips. And I&#8217;m guessing that if you pressed the White HouseÂ on the items on the base-friendly &#8220;counterattack&#8221; list cited by Politico, you would hear an argumentÂ that this agenda isÂ <em>already</em>Â centrist, because (though they wouldn&#8217;t frame it quite this way) itÂ fits neatly into the basic Bloombergist consensus of what the political center should be all about:Â Social liberalism, fiscal responsibility, targeted spending on infrastructure and education, and of course the grail ofÂ immigration reform.</p>
<p style="color: #000000;">There are many things that have gone wrong politically for President Obama since 2009, but a not-insignificant part of the problem is the failure of imagination that the foregoing represents. <span id="more-20489"></span>This White House has long believed â and been encouraged in that belief by center-left pundits âÂ that its policy agenda is actually radically moderate, even Rockefeller Republican, with barely a whiff of real leftism about it. (<em>We took some early-1990s Republican ideas for the design of Obamacare! Our gun control agenda polls well!Â </em>Etc.) Meanwhile, many of the administration&#8217;s critics in the commentariat have long taken as a given that the only way for Obama to move closer to the political middle is to be more aggressively BloombergistÂ â by, say, coming out explicitly in favor of Bowles-Simpson, or some other grand bargain on the deficit; by pushing harder (in some unspecified way) on immigration reform; and so on.</p>
<p style="color: #000000;">This combinationÂ â an administration confident that it&#8217;s already being as bipartisan as possible; a chorus of critics for whom bipartisanship just means grand bargains on taxes and comprehensive cheap-labor billsÂ Â â has become a kind of straitjacket for a president who once, long ago and far away, seemed like he actually had a little more political imagination than that. I&#8217;m afraid it&#8217;s much too late in the day to actually do anything all that substantive about this problem. But if I were advising the president today, I would urge him to come out and say something like the following:</p>
<p style="color: #000000;"><em>The voters have delivered divided government, and in a divided government we have an obligation to find common ground. I feel that I&#8217;ve been trying to do exactly that on tax reform and immigration reform, but without much success. So I&#8217;m going to switch tacks. Over the next few weeks, I&#8217;ll be holding a series of meetings with prominent Republicans on a different set of issues where we might make some headway. First, I&#8217;ll be inviting Senator Rob Portman to the White House to discuss moving forward on the stalled trade agenda. The week after that, I&#8217;ll be inviting Senators Rand Paul and Mike Lee to have a conversation about reforming our drug laws and incarcerationÂ policies. The week following, I&#8217;ll haveÂ Senator Marco Rubio and Congressman Paul Ryan in to discuss how we might find common ground on anti-poverty policy, and particularly on the expansion of the earned-income tax credit they&#8217;ve both endorsed. Then I&#8217;d like to have Senators Lee and Rubio back again to talk about their ideas for reducing the tax burden on working families. And early next year, I&#8217;ll be embarking on a tour of states that voted for Republicans this week, to highlight specific issues (particularly health coverage) where I don&#8217;tÂ think those voters are giving my administration enough credit &#8230; but more importantly to listen, in a variety of formats and settings â churches, community centers, bowling alleys, you name it âÂ to what the people who have voted against my party have to say.</em></p>
<p style="color: #000000;"><em>I&#8217;m not confident that any of these efforts will bear fruit, but I&#8217;m willing to look anew for common ground. So let&#8217;s talk, Republicans, and let&#8217;s have a different conversation than the one that we&#8217;ve been having.Â </em></p>
<p style="color: #000000;">The reality, again, is that none of these forays <em>would</em> be likely to bear any kind of policy fruit, except possibly on trade, not least because several of the figures name-checked are running for president and don&#8217;t particularly want to do a dance of bipartisanship with a lame-duck liberal president. But that wouldn&#8217;t be the point of saying something like this, or scheduling summits and listening tours along these lines. Rather, the point would be twofold: First, just to scramble the issue mix that the president isÂ currently associated with, because the current mix clearly isn&#8217;t working all that well, and second, toÂ make a public gesture of outreach on issues where prominent Republican politicians have <em>already themselves</em> moved toward the center, rather than just trying to stake out a reasonable-seeming position on the issues <em>you</em> want to bargain on (trading tax increases for spending cuts, say) and complaining when the G.O.P. won&#8217;t meet you there. (Or, in the case of sequestration, actually cutting a deal â and then consistently attacking it!)</p>
<p style="color: #000000;">The first kind of outreach isÂ part of what Bill Clinton did after 1994, on welfare reform and a range of more modest issues: He humbled himself a little bit, and let conservatives set the agenda a little bit,Â in a way that this president has never seemed comfortable doing, and ultimately made himself look a little bigger in the process. The environments are, of course, radically different, and there&#8217;s no plausible way for Obama to recreate Clinton&#8217;s success at this late date. But gestures and rhetoric still matter, and there probably <em>is</em> a way (so long as the economy stays okay) for this president to claw his way upward from his current low-40s approval ratings &#8230; which would be the greatest favor he could do his party going into 2016.</p>
<p style="color: #000000;">For that to happen, though, he has to find some way to make himself look like something other than a stumbling block to bipartisanship, and I don&#8217;t see how either more budget negotiations that fruitlessly seekÂ Republican cover for middle class tax increases or more executive unilateralism on other issues are likely to accomplish that. So he should try something else, something new, whether along the lines I&#8217;ve just suggested or in some other shape and form. He should seek to escape, in the two years left to him, the self-imposed ideological narrowing that&#8217;s defined his post-2008 career,Â and the limitedÂ range of choices and postures that the conventional wisdom, left and center, presents him with today.</p>
	</div>
